Prime Minister Phan Van Khai assigned the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs to assist Agent Orange victims by 2000.
The toxic chemical, sprayed by U.S. planes during the Vietnam War, still affects many.
Veterans denied benefits due to strict rules must now be reviewed.
Despite ongoing research, no new evidence links herbicides to diseases.
Vietnamese experts study the effects on civilians and soldiers.
Birth defects and illnesses persist, with no definitive proof of Agent Orange's sole responsibility.
Efforts continue to support and care for those affected by the lasting impact of the war.
